matt-SmartBear
2021-08-04 19:01:24

@channel remember we'd decided we wanted to work from our own machines this time, so I suggest having a go at following through https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js/blob/42538f6b1c4f9d7b6d6d02161f52231bd9077aa6/CONTRIBUTING.md beforehand to get your local dev environment set up.

If you don't have time don't worry, we can make that what we do together.

<https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js/blob/42538f6b1c4f9d7b6d6d02161f52231bd9077aa6/CONTRIBUTING.md | CONTRIBUTING.md>
<p><strong>Thank you!</strong></p> <p>Before anything else, thank you. Thank you for taking some of your precious time helping this project move forward.</p> <p><strong>Setup</strong></p> <p>• install <a href="https://nodejs.org/en/">Node.Js</a> and <a href="https://yarnpkg.com/">Yarn</a> • <code>yarn install</code> - Install dependencies • <code>yarn test</code> - Compile typescript and run the tests</p> <p><strong>Tests</strong></p> <p>Now type <code>yarn run</code> or see the <code>package.json</code> scripts section for how to run each category of tests.</p> <p>• lint - <code>yarn lint</code> • <a href="https://github.com/prettier/prettier">prettier</a> • <a href="https://eslint.org/">eslint</a> • <a href="https://github.com/charlierudolph/dependency-lint">dependency-lint</a> • typescript tests - <code>yarn types-test</code> • <a href="https://github.com/SamVerschueren/tsd">tsd</a> • unit tests - <code>yarn unit-test</code> • <a href="https://mochajs.org/">mocha</a> • <a href="https://www.chaijs.com/">chai</a> • <a href="https://sinonjs.org/">sinon</a> • compatibility kit - <code>yarn cck-test</code> • checking that cucumber-js emits the <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber/tree/master/compatibility-kit">correct messages</a> • feature tests - <code>yarn feature-test</code> • cucumber-js tests itself</p> <p><strong>Internals</strong> <strong>Project Structure</strong></p> <pre><code>└── src │ ├── cli # argv parsing, reading files │ ├── formatter # displaying the results │ ├── models # data structures │ ├── runtime # run test cases, emits the event protocol │ └── support_code_library # load hooks / step definitions </code></pre> <p>The runtime emits events with an <a href="https://nodejs.org/api/events.html#events_class_eventemitter">EventEmitter</a></p> <p><strong>Coding style</strong></p> <p>• Promises and ES7 async/await • Try to make things as unit testable as possible. If it's hard to unit test, the class/function may be doing too much.</p> <p><strong>Changelog</strong></p> <p>• Every PR should have a changelog entry • The contributor should update the changelog • Each entry in the changelog should include a link to the relevant issues/PRs</p> <p><strong>Release process</strong></p> <p><em>The following is a checklist for maintainers when preparing a new release</em></p> <p><strong>Major releases</strong></p> <p>We will always make a release candidate before issuing a major release. The release candidate will be available for at least a month to give users<br /> time to validate that there are no unexpected breaking changes.</p> <p><strong>Process</strong></p> <p>The release is done from the <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-build/">cucumber-build</a> docker container. This makes<br /> sure we use the same environment for all releases.</p> <p><strong>Every command should be run from within the Docker container</strong>.</p> <p>Start the container:</p> <pre><code>make docker-run </code></pre> <p>Inside the container, install the correct versions of Node and Yarn:</p> <pre><code>nvm install --lts npm install -g yarn </code></pre> <p>Then update the dependencies and test:</p> <pre><code>yarn update-dependencies yarn yarn test </code></pre> <p>If the tests fail, update your code to be compatible with the new libraries, or revert the library upgrades that break the build.</p> <p>• Add missing entries to <code>CHANGELOG.md</code> • Ideally the CHANGELOG should be up-to-date, but sometimes there will be accidental omissions when merging PRs. Missing PRs should be added. • Describe the major changes introduced. API changes must be documented. In particular, backward-incompatible changes must be well explained, with examples when possible. • <code>git log --format=format:"** %s (%an)" --reverse &amp;lt;last-version-tag&amp;gt;..HEAD</code> might be handy. • Update the contributors list in <code>package.json</code> • <code>git log --format=format:"%an &amp;lt;%ae&amp;gt;" --reverse &amp;lt;last-version-tag&amp;gt;..HEAD | grep -vEi "(renovate|dependabot|Snyk)" | sort| uniq -i</code> • Manually add contributors (in alphabetical order)</p> <p><a href="https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber/blob/master/RELEASE_PROCESS.md#decide-what-the-next-version-should-be">Decide what the next version should be</a>.</p> <p>Update CHANGELOG links:</p> <pre><code>NEW_VERSION=&amp;lt;major.minor.patch(-rc.X)&amp;gt; make update-changelog </code></pre> <p>Verify changes to the CHANGELOG are correct. Stage uncommitted changes:</p> <pre><code>git add . git commit -am "Release &amp;lt;major.minor.patch(-rc.X)&amp;gt;" </code></pre> <p>Then bump the version number and create a git tag. Run <em>one</em> of the following:</p> <pre><code># Major prelease npm version premajor --preid=rc # Major release npm version major # Minor release npm version minor # Patch release npm version patch </code></pre> <p>Publish to npm:</p> <pre><code>npm publish --access public </code></pre> <p>Push to git:</p> <pre><code>git push git push --tags </code></pre> <p>• Edit and publish the <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js/releases">release entry on GitHub</a> • Update <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/docs.cucumber.io">docs.cucumber.io</a> • Update the cucumber-js version <code>data/versions.yaml</code> • Ensure the javascript examples are up to date</p>
<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js">cucumber/cucumber-js</a>

Cucumber.io
Tackling Structural Racism and Sexism in Open Source
One of the goals the Cucumber team have set ourselves this year is to increase the number of recent, regular contributors who are non-white or non-male from 0 to 2. This post describes why we want to do this, what we’ve learned so far about the systemic barriers that keep the community of p...

Hey <#C028E2TBDJQ|new-contributors>!

A PR has been prepared specially for new contributors. It contains a feature test, your objective would be to make it pass.

That PR contains a detailed step-by-step tutorial that will help you to reach that objective.

The PR is there: https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js/pull/1721 The tutorial is there: https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js/blob/17527667f70c64600adf1ac924336c64b65df66e/docs/first-time-contributor-tutorial.md

matt-SmartBear
2021-08-10 11:36:58

*Thread Reply:* Here's how it would look if that PR was merged: https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js/blob/371c4cb1fa274cbdd2cec4d67d206d3bc103091a/CONTRIBUTING.md

<https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js/blob/371c4cb1fa274cbdd2cec4d67d206d3bc103091a/CONTRIBUTING.md | CONTRIBUTING.md>
<p><strong>Welcome 💖</strong></p> <p>Before anything else, thank you for taking some of your precious time to help this project move forward. ❤️</p> <p>If you're new to open source and feeling a bit nervous 😳, we understand! We recommend watching <a href="https://egghead.io/talks/git-how-to-make-your-first-open-source-contribution">this excellent guide</a><br /> to give you a grounding in some of the basic concepts. We want you to feel safe to make mistakes, and ask questions.</p> <p>If anything in this guide or anywhere else in the codebase doesn't make sense to you, please let us know! It's through your feedback that we can make this codebase more welcoming, so we'll be glad to hear thoughts.</p> <p>You can chat with us in the <a href="https://cucumberbdd.slack.com/archives/C612KCP1P">#committers-js</a> channel in our <a href="https://cucumber.io/community#slack">Community Slack</a>, or feel free to <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js/issues/new/choose">raise an issue</a> if you're experiencing any friction trying make your contribution.</p> <p><strong>Setup</strong></p> <p>• install <a href="https://nodejs.org/en/">Node.Js</a> and <a href="https://yarnpkg.com/">Yarn</a> • <code>yarn install</code> - Install dependencies • <code>yarn test</code> - Compile typescript and run the tests</p> <p><strong>Tests</strong></p> <p>Now type <code>yarn run</code> or see the <code>package.json</code> scripts section for how to run each category of tests.</p> <p>• lint - <code>yarn lint</code> • <a href="https://github.com/prettier/prettier">prettier</a> • <a href="https://eslint.org/">eslint</a> • <a href="https://github.com/charlierudolph/dependency-lint">dependency-lint</a> • typescript tests - <code>yarn types-test</code> • <a href="https://github.com/SamVerschueren/tsd">tsd</a> • unit tests - <code>yarn unit-test</code> • <a href="https://mochajs.org/">mocha</a> • <a href="https://www.chaijs.com/">chai</a> • <a href="https://sinonjs.org/">sinon</a> • compatibility kit - <code>yarn cck-test</code> • checking that cucumber-js emits the <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber/tree/master/compatibility-kit">correct messages</a> • feature tests - <code>yarn feature-test</code> • cucumber-js tests itself</p> <p><strong>Internals</strong> <strong>Project Structure</strong></p> <pre><code>└── src │ ├── cli # argv parsing, reading files │ ├── formatter # displaying the results │ ├── models # data structures │ ├── runtime # run test cases, emits the event protocol │ └── support_code_library # load hooks / step definitions </code></pre> <p>The runtime emits events with an <a href="https://nodejs.org/api/events.html#events_class_eventemitter">EventEmitter</a></p> <p><strong>Coding style</strong></p> <p>• Promises and ES7 async/await • Try to make things as unit testable as possible. If it's hard to unit test, the class/function may be doing too much.</p> <p><strong>Changelog</strong></p> <p>• Every PR should have a changelog entry • The contributor should update the changelog • Each entry in the changelog should include a link to the relevant issues/PRs</p> <p><strong>Release process</strong></p> <p><em>The following is a checklist for maintainers when preparing a new release</em></p> <p><strong>Major releases</strong></p> <p>We will always make a release candidate before issuing a major release. The release candidate will be available for at least a month to give users<br /> time to validate that there are no unexpected breaking changes.</p> <p><strong>Process</strong></p> <p>The release is done from the <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-build/">cucumber-build</a> docker container. This makes<br /> sure we use the same environment for all releases.</p> <p><strong>Every command should be run from within the Docker container</strong>.</p> <p>Start the container:</p> <pre><code>make docker-run </code></pre> <p>Inside the container, install the correct versions of Node and Yarn:</p> <pre><code>nvm install --lts npm install -g yarn </code></pre> <p>Then update the dependencies and test:</p> <pre><code>yarn update-dependencies yarn yarn test </code></pre> <p>If the tests fail, update your code to be compatible with the new libraries, or revert the library upgrades that break the build.</p> <p>• Add missing entries to <code>CHANGELOG.md</code> • Ideally the CHANGELOG should be up-to-date, but sometimes there will be accidental omissions when merging PRs. Missing PRs should be added. • Describe the major changes introduced. API changes must be documented. In particular, backward-incompatible changes must be well explained, with examples when possible. • <code>git log --format=format:"** %s (%an)" --reverse &amp;lt;last-version-tag&amp;gt;..HEAD</code> might be handy. • Update the contributors list in <code>package.json</code> • <code>git log --format=format:"%an &amp;lt;%ae&amp;gt;" --reverse &amp;lt;last-version-tag&amp;gt;..HEAD | grep -vEi "(renovate|dependabot|Snyk)" | sort| uniq -i</code> • Manually add contributors (in alphabetical order)</p> <p><a href="https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber/blob/master/RELEASE_PROCESS.md#decide-what-the-next-version-should-be">Decide what the next version should be</a>.</p> <p>Update CHANGELOG links:</p> <pre><code>NEW_VERSION=&amp;lt;major.minor.patch(-rc.X)&amp;gt; make update-changelog </code></pre> <p>Verify changes to the CHANGELOG are correct. Stage uncommitted changes:</p> <pre><code>git add . git commit -am "Release &amp;lt;major.minor.patch(-rc.X)&amp;gt;" </code></pre> <p>Then bump the version number and create a git tag. Run <em>one</em> of the following:</p> <pre><code># Major prelease npm version premajor --preid=rc # Major release npm version major # Minor release npm version minor # Patch release npm version patch </code></pre> <p>Publish to npm:</p> <pre><code>npm publish --access public </code></pre> <p>Push to git:</p> <pre><code>git push git push --tags </code></pre> <p>• Edit and publish the <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js/releases">release entry on GitHub</a> • Update <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/docs.cucumber.io">docs.cucumber.io</a> • Update the cucumber-js version <code>data/versions.yaml</code> • Ensure the javascript examples are up to date</p>
<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js">cucumber/cucumber-js</a>

*Thread Reply:* TBH, I don't have much to say about JavaScript, so don't meet on my account.

That said, I do have things to say about CI/CD tooling and I think the team could benefit from some more automation for things like code style and boilerplate scaffolding.

This article sums up a list of the usual suspects. https://www.softwaretestingmagazine.com/tools/open-source-javascript-code-analysis/

Software Testing Magazine
Open Source JavaScript Code Analysis
The quality of the JavaScript code is often verified with the traditional activities of unit and functional testing. There are however tools that allow checking code before or during its execution to assess its quality and its adherence to coding standards using a process called code analysis. This article presents a list of open source tools to perform static and dynamic code analysis on JavaScript programs. If static code analysis can be performed individually on each piece of JavaScript code, modern software development organizations will integrate these tools in their continuous integration or delivery process. This automated approach prevents code that is bad or doesn't respect the coding standards to reach the production stage. Dynamic code analysis the software when it is performed by executing programs on a real or virtual processor. The two main know open source tools used for JavaScript code analysis are JSLint and JSHint, the second being a fork of the first one. Developed by the famous Douglas Crockford, JSLint can be considered as the main inspiration of the JavaScript open source code analysis tools family. There are however many different tools that try to achieve the same goal and you might find something more suited to your own needs in the list below, especially if you work in specific JavaScript frameworks and contexts like Node.js, Angular, React, Vue, Express or TypeScript. Updates December 15 2020 * added Nocuous, JScent, JSDeodorant, Semgrep April 2019 * added Codelyzer, CodeClimmate-Duplication, NodeJsScan, SourceCodeSniffer * removed JSCS JavaScript Code Style &lt;a class="mh-excerpt-more" href="https://www.softwaretestingmagazine.com/tools/open-source-javascript-code-analysis/" title="Open Source JavaScript Code Analysis"&gt;[...]&lt;/a&gt;
Original URL: https://www.softwaretestingmagazine.com/tools/open-source-javascript-code-analysis/

<https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js/issues/1735|#1735 Cucumber's own features fail when parent directory contains parentheses>
<p><strong>Describe the bug</strong><br /> Whenever the parent directory has parentheses in its name, I noticed the cucumber features tests start to fail. I also noticed that in the tests that are run, the path for the parent directory drops the parentheses from the path name. For the above reason, the path can not be found for a specified directory.</p> <pre><code>22) Scenario: # features/usage_json_formatter.feature:8 ✔ Before # ../../Cucumber x/cucumber-js/src/support_code_library_builder/build_helpers.ts:13 ✔ Given a file named "features/a.feature" with: # ../../Cucumber x/cucumber-js/src/support_code_library_builder/build_helpers.ts:13 """ Feature: a feature Scenario: a scenario Given step A And step A When step B Then step C """ ✔ And a file named "features/step_definitions/steps.js" with: # ../../Cucumber x/cucumber-js/src/support_code_library_builder/build_helpers.ts:13 """ const {When} = require('@cucumber/cucumber') When('step A', function() {}); When('step B', function() {}); When('step C', function() {}); When(/step D/, function() {}); """ ✔ When I run cucumber-js with `--format usage-json` # ../../Cucumber x/cucumber-js/src/support_code_library_builder/build_helpers.ts:13 ✖ Then it outputs the usage data: # ../../Cucumber x/cucumber-js/src/support_code_library_builder/build_helpers.ts:13 | PATTERN | PATTERN_TYPE | URI | LINE | NUMBER OF MATCHES | | step A | CucumberExpression | features/step_definitions/steps.js | 3 | 2 | | step B | CucumberExpression | features/step_definitions/steps.js | 4 | 1 | | step C | CucumberExpression | features/step_definitions/steps.js | 5 | 1 | | step D | RegularExpression | features/step_definitions/steps.js | 6 | 0 | AssertionError + expected - actual -13 +3 at /Users/emmanuelola/Documents/Cucumber (x)/cucumber-js/features/step_definitions/usage_json_steps.ts:15:30 at Array.forEach (&amp;lt;anonymous&amp;gt;) at World.&amp;lt;anonymous&amp;gt; (/Users/emmanuelola/Documents/Cucumber (x)/cucumber-js/features/step_definitions/usage_json_steps.ts:9:18) ✔ After # ../../Cucumber x/cucumber-js/src/support_code_library_builder/build_helpers.ts:13 </code></pre> <p><strong>To Reproduce</strong><br /> Steps to reproduce the behavior:</p> <ol><li>Go to 'the root directory for the project'</li><li>Add a parent directory with a parentheses in its name (include some letters within the parentheses)</li><li>Open the project in your desired IDE</li><li>Run the tests</li><li>See error</li> </ol> <p><strong>Expected behavior</strong><br /> Passing tests</p> <p><strong>Screenshots</strong><br /> <a href="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/54866720/126218939-c2815926-79e2-4b3e-9af5-0bf987e8598f.png">Untitled</a></p> <p><strong>Desktop (please complete the following information):</strong></p> <p>• OS: macOS Big Sur 11.4 • Version: Main Repository Branch</p> <p><strong>Additional context</strong><br /> Trying to run tests to contribute to cucumber-js with <a href="https://github.com/mattwynne">@mattwynne</a> as part of the Cucumber first timers mob and the folder where I keep my code happens to have parentheses in its name. For more context, this is not the folder shown in the screenshot, that's simply provided for testing purposes.</p>

<https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js/pull/1824|#1824 Fix-1735 Parentheses in developers' paths break cucumber's own tests WIP>

<p><strong>What we liked:</strong></p> <p>• small pieces / small steps • screensharing - made it easy to switch over, like when Demi left • liked talking about cars! - personal connection is really important. • liked the explanation of the World. Hugely valuable for Blaise! Cucumber ecosystem struggles defining these concepts for newcomers. • A clear objective with many similar, small examples of it. Easy to shift context from one problem to the next, even though they were all slightly different. • we just kept rolling when Blaise arrived and Demi left. • Kate coming along even though she didn't feel she had a lot to contribute</p> <p><strong>Anything we would do differently? Puzzles?</strong></p> <p>• Took half an hour to get started - setting up the environment, etc. A script to get everything set up beforehand? I've done my homework already! (see https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js/pull/1893)

<https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-js/pull/1893|#1893 Extract prettier config from eslintrc>
<p><strong>Description</strong></p> <p>Use a more conventional place to store prettier config</p> <p><strong>Motivation &amp; context</strong></p> <p>So that VSCode's prettier plugin can automatically find it.</p> <p>Currently, VSCode doesn't understand our prettier config, so the code formatter from the prettier plugin reformats the code using defaults (e.g. adding semi-colons), which then breaks the eslint rules!</p> <p><strong>Type of change</strong></p> <p>• Refactoring/debt (improvement to code design or tooling without changing behaviour)</p>

For the gpg stuff I had to brew install pinentry-mac and edit my ~/.gnupg/gpg-agent.conf to add:

pinentry-program /opt/homebrew/bin/pinentry-mac That then started popping up an OSX prompt for the passphrase instead of one in the CLI, and that included a box to check where I could save it into my keychain. I'm sure I've had this set up before, so it must be something that slipped loose in an OS upgrade or something.

Aslak Hellesøy
2022-01-18 08:40:21

*Thread Reply:* In the Cucumber 10 minutes tutorial we state that some prerequisite knowledge is needed. This was decided in this issue.

The Cucumber School videos also require some prerequisite knowledge, but I'm not sure if it's stated as explicitly as in the 10 min tutorial. I would assume it would be similar.

@matt-SmartBear I think we should make this explicit to avoid people feeling like @Kate Dames did. That said, I'm all for helping people out, but they should know what they are getting into before they start.

<https://github.com/cucumber/docs/issues/647|#647 Add a note in the introduction of the 10 minutes tutorial to inform that it prerequisites basic development knowledge>
<p>The "10 min tutorials" on <a href="https://docs.cucumber.io/docs/guides/10-minute-tutorial/">https://docs.cucumber.io/docs/guides/10-minute-tutorial/</a> are frustrating to use. It presume much from the readers when it suddenly swift between Command-promt windows and Ruby etc. between steps. It presumes that that the reader would understand "Gemfile", let alone how to use them.</p> <p>This may be enough information for someone who already know Ruby and Cucumber from the get-go (which would make a tutorial unnecessary by definition), but when you're a new user who only know "enough" to get around, but not to get into every crevasse, then it's a frustrating experience. It feels at times as if you get talk down to for them not knowing what the tutorial, by definition, should have been able to tell me in the first place.</p> <p><strong>Describe the solution you'd like</strong><br /> Images/Screenshots that shows when and where you are at any given point. To show where you as a reader are when the tutorial-text jump around in the menu. To show which window/command window etc. you're currently in at any given moment.</p> <p>Describe alternatives you've considered<br /> Bulleting, that clearly states the How and Where to do the how.</p> <p>Additional context<br /> (See image for reference).<br /> That is just an example of the "installing process". There are plenty more in the text, but for this example, you can see the attatched screenshot for reference.</p> <p>1: It start with "We’ll start by creating a new directory and an empty Ruby project." (In the same project or as two separate entities? Is the directory specific to the project or a new default? Should the directory be called something specific (like Gemfile) or is that optional?)</p> <p>Then it goes down to "Create a Gemfile with the following content:" - As a new user and as a ready, the question on ones mind is "Where?" In the directory? In the project file itself? In a new place? Should the Gemfile be given a specific filetype? (like Gemfile.rb?) Should the reader just write-in the versions as they are presented on the sire (Screenshot), or should they use the command-promt to find the right versions? (cucumber -version or other similar?). Does it matter?</p> <p>Thirdly, we get to "Install Cucumber and prepare the file structure:" - Again, is that in Ruby or in command promt? Is the reader still in the Gemfile? Should this be added at the start of a new [File].feature?</p> <p>I hope that this shows the issue I personally have had as a new user. The tutorial jump left and right with little explanation or consideration to anyone who supposedly not already possesses enough knowledge to make a tutorial void in the first place. It is called a "10 minutes tutorial", but personally, I have yet to reach the end of the tutorial. This is frustrating, partly due to the aforementioned "jumps", but also when you do manage to follow the tutorial, since when you come across an issue that halt one process, then you don't know why. This is especially an issue when it comes to writing an issue-report or asking for help, because you cannot be sure that you installed things right in the first place.</p> <p><a href="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/86303765/123971315-38802a00-d9ba-11eb-8c5e-0ece0b201caf.PNG">text ex</a></p>

<p><strong>2022-01-21</strong> <strong>Who</strong></p> <p>• Kate Dames • Blaise Pabon • Matt Wynne</p> <p><strong>What happened</strong></p> <p>• Kate and Blaise showed up 2 weeks in a row! • We talked about the docs, and their shortcomings • We decided we wanted a real example of Cucumber used in practice • We looked at <a href="https://github.com/gothinkster/realworld">https://github.com/gothinkster/realworld</a> • We decided to start work on the thingy to retire inactive contributors (<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/commitbit/issues/3">cucumber/commitbit#3</a>) • We made an example map: <a href="https://miro.com/app/board/uXjVOVYhVEw=/?moveToWidget=3458764517125398282&amp;cot=14|https://miro.com/app/board/uXjVOVYhVEw=/?moveToWidget=3458764517125398282&amp;cot=14">https://miro.com/app/board/uXjVOVYhVEw=/?moveToWidget=3458764517125398282&amp;cot=14|https://miro.com/app/board/uXjVOVYhVEw=/?moveToWidget=3458764517125398282&amp;cot=14</a> • We had this retro</p> <p><strong>Insights</strong></p> <p>• Kate liked that we're using a real-world example. • Kate liked going through the example mapping looking at actual data in the examples - e.g. Greg, Julien etc. • Kate liked that we used Miro for collaboration to pin-down our thoughts - park some things for later etc. • Blaise liked doing example mapping in action, so concretely. Learning the distinctions between a rule / example and a story. • Blaise: Materials used to teach cucumber don't emphasise the end result (e.g. the intermediate progress towards a goal). Also don't emphasis how you can use a single test to run against multiple implementations. • Matt: Our docs don't give people enough context as they arrive - straight into the guts of installation without any signposts • Matt: How much we discovered about a problem I thought was simple. I love example mapping! • Kate: I wanted to be more actively participating in the miro board. More hands on. Was it a lack of familiarity? Should we have mad more formal mob roles? What are the rules of the example mapping game? • Kate: It was fun, thankyou!</p> <p><strong>Actions</strong></p> <p>• Matt: figure out where we should implement this - in the existing commitbit repo or somewhere else? • Kate: think about the process and formalising exmaple mapping</p>

matt-SmartBear
2022-01-27 14:57:59

Folks, in terms of an agenda / plan for tomorrow's ensemble, I suggest we carry on with the work we started last week, to build some GitHub automation to help us retire inactive contributors into an "alumni" team, to keep our security tight.

Last week we did some example mapping to figure out the details of our first couple of stories, so this week I think we can turn that into some Gherkin scenarios, in a real git repo.

My homework from last time was to figure out roughly how we'd implement this, and I think that a https://probot.github.io/ is probably the way to go.

So we'll create a new repo, and follow these instructions to generate a stub probot app. Then we can start writing some Gherkin scenarios in that repo.

If we get time, we can start looking at how to wire those scenarios up, referring to this article in the probot docs about testing.

How does that sound?

I'd appreciate a ✋:skintone2: emoji if you're planning to attend tomorrow. It always helps me if I know who's going to be able to show up.

For the specific context of our new contributors ensemble, There are a few things I do to communicate about the ensemble that would be useful to be more systematic about.

Maybe this could be a 3rd row, called "communications" or something?

Day Before: • send out a message on <#C028E2TBDJQ|new-contributors> suggesting what we'll work on, and asking for ✋:skintone2: from folks who think they'll attend. • send out a Tweet with a link to the Twitch stream (https://twitch.tv/cucumberbdd) Hour before: • Send a message on <#C028E2TBDJQ|new-contributors> with a link to the Zoom, reminding that all are welcome • send out a Tweet with a link to the twitch stream During the session: • When everyone's ready, start OBS recording and streaming to twitch. • send out a Tweet with a link to the twitch stream, saying we're live. • send a slack message in #announcements with a link to the twitch stream, saying we're live. • watch the Twitch stream for comments or questions After: • Upload the video of the session to YouTube. Title is of the form "Kate, Blaise & Matt work on Cucumber-JVM". Add a brief description of what we did in the session. • Add the YouTube video to the "New contributors ensemble" playlist • Send a message to the <#C028E2TBDJQ|new-contributors> channel summarising what we did, with a link to the retro and the youtube video.

*Thread Reply:* On the marketing thing, I think of it as "communications" rather than marketing, because we're not trying to sell anything. *Thread Reply:* One concern I have with the value judgements as stated is that the things on the right (judgement, exclusion, criticism) are not things I would value, so they don't really represent difficult choices because I'd be happy to give them up.

I'd prefer to find things for the right-hand-side that we also value and that we recognise are in conflict with the things on the left, but that we're willing to let go of because the things on the left matter more to us.

Blaise Pabon
2022-02-18 05:04:59

*Thread Reply:* What I mean is (and I don't mean this as a bad thing), most JavaScript activity is around overcoming issues with JavaScript. It's a language for writing code, not so much for running code.

In that sense, a real language would be one that can address many levels of abstraction, be tested with a higher than necessary degree of confidence (including external dependencies), and produce reusable components.

matt-SmartBear
2022-02-18 14:35:52

I figured out the issue with the git mobbers plugin.

It searches for co-authors in the commit history of the current repo, and it doesn't list people who were co-authors, so none of you appear because all of our commits in this repo have been made in an ensemble.

Fortunately though, it also syncs with the git-mob CLI tool which allows you to manually add to the list of potential co-authors.

Phew!

<https://github.com/rkotze/git-mob-vs-code/issues/77|#77 Include co-author only contributors into the "more authors" list>
<a href="https://github.com/rkotze/git-mob-vs-code">rkotze/git-mob-vs-code</a>
:dancing_pickle: Kate Dames, Blaise Pabon

Spotify Engineering
When Should I Write an Architecture Decision Record
TL;DR Have you made a significant decision that impacts how engineers write software? Write an ADR! An Architecture Decision Record (ADR) is a document that captures a decision, including the context of how the decision was made and the consequences of adopting the decision. At Spotify, a handfu

matt-SmartBear
2022-03-11 10:00:16

*Thread Reply:* My favourite example of this type of thing was from last week when I was going backcountry ski touring in an area with no phone signal. I have a Garmin InReach which is a satellite / GPS device that lets me send an SOS signal via satellite if we get into trouble. Really cool little device!

I tested it before I left - I'd used it 2 weeks before that and it worked fine - and this time the message didn't come through. I got on the phone with Garmin tech support and it turned out that I needed to install a "critical software update" for it to work!!!

Good job I wasn't stuck on the side of a mountain with a broken leg!

Backwards compatibility is a thing, people.

<p><strong>🤔 What's changed?</strong></p> <p>• Added an <a href="https://adr.github.io/">ADR</a> about moving from Probot -&gt; GitHub Actions</p> <p><strong>⚡ What's your motivation?</strong></p> <p>Document the context around the decision, for transparency and future reference.</p> <p><strong>🏷️ What kind of change is this?</strong></p> <p>• 🏦 Refactoring/debt (improvement to code design or tooling without changing behaviour)</p> <p><strong>♻️ Anything particular you want feedback on?</strong></p> <p>• Does what I've written reflect your understanding of the decision? • Is anything unclear?</p> <p><strong>📋 Checklist:</strong></p> <p>☑︎ I agree to respect and uphold the <a href="https://cucumber.io/conduct/">Cucumber Community Code of Conduct</a> ☐ I've changed the behaviour of the code ☐ I have added/updated tests to cover my changes. ☑︎ My change requires a change to the documentation. ☑︎ I have updated the documentation accordingly. ☐ Users should know about my change ☐ I have added an entry to the "Unreleased" section of the &lt;../CHANGELOG.md|<strong>CHANGELOG</strong>&gt;, linking to this pull request.</p>

<p><strong>🤔 What's changed?</strong></p> <p>• Removed all files generated by Probot scaffolding command • Removed <code>npm</code> packages only used by probot</p> <p><strong>⚡ What's your motivation?</strong></p> <p>Given we're <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributor/blob/main/doc/adr/0001-implement-as-a-github-action-not-a-probot.md">no longer using probot</a> there's a bunch of stuff in this repo that we don't need. 2022-05-03 14:13:34

So, I am getting used to our new rhythm - tommorow (Wednesday at 18:00 UTC) is our next new-contributors ensemble. Everyone is welcome!

We've been working on https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributor and our next step is to continue building out the implementation of our main https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributor/blob/main/src/retireInactiveContributors.ts function to make our two WIP scenarios pass.

We'll be writing TypeScript, building a GitHub Action. If you've never worked with that tech before thought, that's OK. One of our manifesto commitments is Exploration Over Perfection:

> we are here to learn, and always discovering better ways to do things; we embrace experimentation and accept that what we do can never be perfect. @channel please give me a 👍:skintone2: if you're planning to attend, and ping me your email if you need adding to the calendar invite.

matt-SmartBear
2022-05-24 14:18:52

So tomorrow we'll be running the new contributors ensemble. We've been working on https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributor and last week we reached an exciting milestone that our first two scenarios are passing!

However, those scenarios use our FakeGithub adapter, which stubs out those all-important calls to the Github API. To have a working tool, we need another implementation of our Github port, which we're calling OctokitGithub . This adapter will use the Octokit library and make actual calls to the Github API.

We should be able to test-drive the implementation of this new adapter, using the github.com/test-inactive-contributor-action org as a sandbox.

We also said that we wanted to start using Github Issues more, and have at least a medium-term plan so we know where we're going and what's left to do. So we might want to start with that.

Give us a 👍:skintone2: if you're planning to attend.

*Thread Reply:* Hey @Blaise Pabon Stop looking, start writing! 😛 Can you remember what Matt said the essence of quality in Zen and the art of motorcycle maintenance was?

matt-SmartBear
2022-06-28 08:01:45

*Thread Reply:* > "Quality is whatever you like" This is sort of a straw-man that he puts up early on in the book, not really what I agree with, but it's one interpretation.

🤓 Kate Dames
matt-SmartBear
2022-06-28 08:03:12

*Thread Reply:* > "Quality...you know what it is, yet you don’t know what it is. But that’s self-contradictory. But some things are better than others, that is, they have more quality. But when you try to say what the quality is, apart from the things that have it, it all goes poof! There’s nothing to talk about. But if you can’t say what Quality is, how do you know what it is, or how do you know that it even exists? If no one knows what it is, then for all practical purposes it doesn’t exist at all. But for all practical purposes it really does exist.”

matt-SmartBear
2022-06-28 08:04:43

*Thread Reply:* > “Care and Quality are internal and external aspects of the same thing. A person who sees Quality and feels it as he works is a person who cares. A person who cares about what he sees and does is a person who’s bound to have some characteristic of quality.”

😍 Kate Dames

*Thread Reply:* 2. We should submit it as a fix for https://github.com/kubernetes/org/issues/2052

<https://github.com/kubernetes/org/issues/2052|#2052 Create tool for removing org members>
<p>We intend to start doing a regular cleanup of inactive members (<a href="https://github.com/kubernetes/org/issues/2013">#2013</a>, <a href="https://github.com/kubernetes/org/pull/2047">#2047</a>).</p> <p>Removing org members means removing them from the config files in this repo. Removing them manually is tedious so we need to create an automated tool that can help us do that.</p> <p>EDIT(spiffxp): <a href="https://github.com/kubernetes/org/pull/2458">#2458</a> merged the prior art we have in in bash, but we would rather have a tool written in something more testable, less brittle (e.g. Go)</p>

<p><strong>🤔 What's the problem you're trying to solve?</strong></p> <p>To finish our first main story, we need to implement this method so that our real <code>OctokitGitHub</code> client can call GitHub to remove a user from the main team when moving them into the alumni team.</p> <p><strong>✨ What's your proposed solution?</strong></p> <p>• Add another test similar to <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributor/blob/main/src/OctokitGitHub.test.ts#L7">https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributor/blob/main/src/OctokitGitHub.test.ts#L7</a> to test the <code>removeUserFromTeam</code> method. This one will need to add a user in the test setup. • Steal the code from <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributor/blob/main/src/OctokitGitHub.test.ts#L20-L24">https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributor/blob/main/src/OctokitGitHub.test.ts#L20-L24</a> for the body of the <code>removeUserFromTeam</code> method.</p> <p><strong>📚 Any additional context?</strong></p> <p><a href="https://miro.com/app/board/uXjVOPyvsOw=/?moveToWidget=3458764531039463975&amp;cot=14|https://miro.com/app/board/uXjVOPyvsOw=/?moveToWidget=3458764531039463975&amp;cot=14">https://miro.com/app/board/uXjVOPyvsOw=/?moveToWidget=3458764531039463975&amp;cot=14|https://miro.com/app/board/uXjVOPyvsOw=/?moveToWidget=3458764531039463975&amp;cot=14</a></p> <hr /> <p><em>This text was originally generated from a <a href="https://docs.github.com/en/communities/using-templates-to-encourage-useful-issues-and-pull-requests/about-issue-and-pull-request-templates">template</a>, then edited by hand. <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/.github/edit/main/.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/feature_request.md">You can modify the template here.</a></em></p>

TIL https://tryapis.com/github/api/actions-download-workflow-run-attempt-logs

tryapis.com
GitHub API | Download workflow run attempt logs
Instantly send requests to the GitHub API. Gets a redirect URL to download an archive of log files for a specific workflow run attempt. This link expires after 1 minute. Look for `Location:` in the response header to find the URL for the download. Anyone with read access to the repository can use this endpoint. If the repository is private you must use an access token with the `repo` scope. GitHub Apps must have the `actions:read` permission to use this endpoint.
Original URL: https://tryapis.com/github/api/actions-download-workflow-run-attempt-logs

#406 WANTED: More regular maintainers :wrench::woman-raising-hand::man-raising-hand::skin-tone-5::raising_hand::skin-tone-3:
<p>Since Cucumber adopted this project, the bulk of the maintenance effort has fallen to just <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/godog/graphs/contributors">one or two individuals</a>.</p> <p>While we're super-grateful to those individuals, this situation puts too much pressure on those individuals and is unsustainable. Right now, with those people busy with other stuff, pull requests and issues are starting to pile up. Thanks to <a href="https://github.com/vearutop">@vearutop</a> who's already started to <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/godog/commit/9a335aed221fadf59b68323742f2189f4a5d782b">step in and help</a>. 🙏:skin<em>tone</em>2:</p> <p>It's clear from the number of GitHub stars that lots of people are using this project. I'm raising this issue as a call to the Go community to see who would like to get more involved.</p> <p>Some reasons to step forward:</p> <p>• Be a part of a welcoming community of developers who take test-driven development for granted. 🚀🎉 • Know that the Cucumber community has an explicit commitment to diversity, <a href="https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/625404/equity-vs-equality-what-is-the-difference">equity</a> and inclusion and that if you're from an under-represented minority in tech, you'll be welcome here. ✊:skin<em>tone</em>6:🏳️‍🌈❤️ • Cucumber has an active set of sponsors which allows people to <a href="https://opencollective.com/cucumber#category-BUDGET">get paid for their contributions</a>. 💰</p> <p>Here are some ways you can help the project:</p> <p>• <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/common/blob/main/TRIAGE.md">Triage</a> existing issues • Review/triage other people's pull requests • Submit pull requests that (at least partially) solve an issue. • Merge pull requests (once you have the commit bit) • Join community discussions about <a href="https://github.com/go-bdd/gobdd/issues/137">bigger strategic changes</a></p> <p>All of these are helpful and very much appreciated.</p> <p>We have limited Go fluency in the team of regular maintainers at the moment, but we're here to help and available to pair with you if you need help figuring something out.</p> <p>If you're willing to help, please let us know in the comments, or come for a chat in the <a href="https://cucumber.io/community#slack">Community Slack</a> in the <a href="https://cucumberbdd.slack.com/archives/CA5NJPDJ4">#commiters-go</a> channel.</p>
<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/godog">cucumber/godog</a>

matt-SmartBear
2023-01-25 12:44:47

This week we have finished off getting the dry-run flag through from the action yaml into our code, and tested it. We broke up our GitHub Actions test workflow into three separate workflows, so we can test the dry-run on it's own. It seems to work!

First we see https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributor/actions/runs/4009784788 where it logs that it found 2 users and says it's moved them, but when we looked at the test org afterwards, nothing had happened.

Then it ran https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributor/actions/runs/4009786692 and that one did move them into the alumni team, as expected.

matt-SmartBear
2023-01-25 12:50:08

We noticed that the logging from dry-run isn't super clear:

• the note about "Reviewing permissions for 2 users" doesn't tell you where it found those two users, so reporting the user and what existing permissions they were found to have would be helpful. • when it says "Adding/Removing user x to alumni" it looks the same whether you're in dry-run mode or not, which is a bit confusing. It would be better if it said something to indicate that it would have added or removed them, but it's in dry run mode. So you can clearly see whether it's actually taking action or not.

matt-SmartBear
2023-01-25 12:50:38

Most importantly, THINGS WORK ON LISA'S MACHINE! We did the whole session from her hosted live share and it all worked!

@Lisa Crispin here's the heart of Cucumber (Ruby):

https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-ruby-core/blob/main/lib/cucumber/core/test/runner.rb

Maybe a candidate for code-reading club?

<https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-ruby-core/blob/main/lib/cucumber/core/test/runner.rb | runner.rb>
<pre><code># frozen_string_literal: true require 'cucumber/core/test/timer' module Cucumber module Core module Test class Runner attr_reader :event_bus, :running_test_case, :running_test_step private :event_bus, :running_test_case, :running_test_step def initialize(event_bus) @event_bus = event_bus end def test_case(test_case, &amp;descend) @running_test_case = RunningTestCase.new @running_test_step = nil event_bus.test_case_started(test_case) descend.call(self) result = running_test_case.result result = Result::Undefined.new('The test case has no steps', Result::UnknownDuration.new, ["#{test_case.location}:in `#{test_case.name}'"]) if result.unknown? event_bus.test_case_finished(test_case, result) self end def test_step(test_step) @running_test_step = test_step event_bus.test_step_started test_step step_result = running_test_case.execute(test_step) event_bus.test_step_finished test_step, step_result @running_test_step = nil self end def around_hook(hook, &amp;continue) result = running_test_case.execute(hook, &amp;continue) event_bus.test_step_finished running_test_step, result if running_test_step @running_test_step = nil self end def done self end class RunningTestCase def initialize @timer = Timer.new.start @status = Status::Unknown.new(Result::Unknown.new) end def execute(test_step, &amp;continue) status.execute(test_step, self, &amp;continue) end def result status.result(@timer.duration) end def failed(step_result) @status = Status::Failing.new(step_result) self end def passed(step_result) @status = Status::Passing.new(step_result) self end def pending(message, step_result) @status = Status::Pending.new(step_result) self end def skipped(step_result) @status = Status::Skipping.new(step_result) self end def undefined(step_result) failed(step_result) self end def exception(step_exception, step_result) self end def duration(step_duration, step_result) self end attr_reader :status private :status module Status class Base attr_reader :step_result private :step_result def initialize(step_result) @step_result = step_result end def execute(test_step, monitor, &amp;continue) result = test_step.execute(monitor.result, &amp;continue) result = result.with_message(%(Undefined step: "#{test_step.text}")) if result.undefined? result = result.with_appended_backtrace(test_step) unless test_step.hook? result.describe_to(monitor, result) end def result raise NoMethodError, "Override me" end end class Unknown &lt; Base def result(duration) Result::Unknown.new end end class Passing &lt; Base def result(duration) Result::Passed.new(duration) end end class Failing &lt; Base def execute(test_step, monitor, &amp;continue) result = test_step.skip(monitor.result) if result.undefined? result = result.with_message(%(Undefined step: "#{test_step.text}")) result = result.with_appended_backtrace(test_step) end result end def result(duration) step_result.with_duration(duration) end end Pending = Class.new(Failing) class Skipping &lt; Failing def result(duration) step_result.with_duration(duration) end end end end end end end end </code></pre>
<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-ruby-core">cucumber/cucumber-ruby-core</a>

What's our plan today? We have this PR that needs to be reviewed and (hopefully) merged: https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/pull/48

#48 Refactor to use a readonly GithubClient in dry-run mode
<p><strong>🤔 What's changed?</strong></p> <p>• Added a <code>ReadOnlyGitHubClient</code>decorator class which implements the <code>GitHubClient</code> interface, wrapping a <code>GitHubClient</code> and only calling through to the read-only methods (<code>hasCommittedSince</code> and <code>getMembersOf</code>). • Modified the main <code>retireInactiveContributors</code> function to wrap its <code>github</code> parameter with the <code>ReadOnlyGitHubClient</code> if in dry-run mode, and remove the other conditionals.</p> <p><strong>⚡ What's your motivation?</strong></p> <p>Refactoring suggested in the checklist for <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/issues/45">#45</a></p> <p><strong>🏷️ What kind of change is this?</strong></p> <p>• 🏦 Refactoring/debt/DX (improvement to code design, tooling, documentation etc. without changing behaviour)</p> <p><strong>♻️ Anything particular you want feedback on?</strong></p> <p>Does this make sense?</p> <p><strong>📋 Checklist:</strong></p> <p>☑︎ I agree to respect and uphold the <a href="https://cucumber.io/conduct/">Cucumber Community Code of Conduct</a></p> <hr /> <p><em>This text was originally generated from a <a href="https://docs.github.com/en/communities/using-templates-to-encourage-useful-issues-and-pull-requests/about-issue-and-pull-request-templates">template</a>, then edited by hand. <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/.github/edit/main/.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md">You can modify the template here.</a></em></p>

#45 dry-run mode
<p><strong>🤔 What's the problem you're trying to solve?</strong></p> <p>We'd like to try this out for real on the <code>cucumber</code> org, but this is a bit nerve-wracking!</p> <p>First, it would be good to add a <code>dry-run</code> option so we can find out what it <em>would</em> do, without it actually doing it.</p> <p><strong>📚 Any additional context?</strong></p> <p>Thanks to <a href="https://github.com/ALCooper12">@ALCooper12</a> for this suggestion!</p> <p><strong>Todo</strong></p> <p>☑︎ implement test and logic to do dry-run or not depending on config setting ☐ refactor ☑︎ consider using a more expressive type for the <code>dryRun</code> attribute on the <code>Configuration</code> class (done in <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/commit/c24e377ac5b6adfc407a995ea0628307820d19f4">c24e377</a>) ☐ consider using a <a href="https://refactoring.guru/design-patterns/decorator/typescript/example">decorator</a> for the GitHub class when we're in dry-run mode (See <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/pull/48">#48</a>) ☐ do we want the same activity logging in dry-run mode, or different? ☑︎ set the config setting from the action.yml</p> <hr /> <p><em>This text was originally generated from a <a href="https://docs.github.com/en/communities/using-templates-to-encourage-useful-issues-and-pull-requests/about-issue-and-pull-request-templates">template</a>, then edited by hand. <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/.github/edit/main/.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/feature_request.md">You can modify the template here.</a></em></p>

#45 dry-run mode
<p><strong>🤔 What's the problem you're trying to solve?</strong></p> <p>We'd like to try this out for real on the <code>cucumber</code> org, but this is a bit nerve-wracking!</p> <p>First, it would be good to add a <code>dry-run</code> option so we can find out what it <em>would</em> do, without it actually doing it.</p> <p><strong>📚 Any additional context?</strong></p> <p>Thanks to <a href="https://github.com/ALCooper12">@ALCooper12</a> for this suggestion!</p> <p><strong>Todo</strong></p> <p>☑︎ implement test and logic to do dry-run or not depending on config setting ☑︎ refactor ☑︎ consider using a more expressive type for the <code>dryRun</code> attribute on the <code>Configuration</code> class (done in <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/commit/c24e377ac5b6adfc407a995ea0628307820d19f4">c24e377</a>) ☑︎ consider using a <a href="https://refactoring.guru/design-patterns/decorator/typescript/example">decorator</a> for the GitHub class when we're in dry-run mode (See <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/pull/48">#48</a>) ☑︎ make activity logging reflect dry-run mode? <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/pull/49">PR</a> ☐ change <code>dry-run</code> to <code>read-only</code> ☑︎ set the config setting from the action.yml</p> <hr /> <p><em>This text was originally generated from a <a href="https://docs.github.com/en/communities/using-templates-to-encourage-useful-issues-and-pull-requests/about-issue-and-pull-request-templates">template</a>, then edited by hand. <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/.github/edit/main/.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/feature_request.md">You can modify the template here.</a></em></p>

*Thread Reply:* Wired: we reached a bit of a milestone by adding a schedule workflow for the action.

Next: Implement a version scheme to fix https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/issues/51 (I'll ask @mpkorstanje)

#51 Semver 2.0 releases
<p><strong>🤔 What's the problem you're trying to solve?</strong></p> <p>Within the Cucumber organisation we pin GitHub actions to a specific version to ensure that builds don't break unexpectedly.</p> <p>This means that as an organisation we have many version numbers to keep track of. To maintain these we use <a href="https://renovatebot.com/">Renovate</a>. Renovate will update a version and then submit a pull request.</p> <p>We have configured Renovate such that when patch or minor versions updates are made the pull request is skipped and if the CI is passing the update is quitely merged with the main branch.</p> <p>Unfortunately this plugin doesn't have any official releases. Instead we pin against a git hash. This means we can't tell Renovate to quitely update it. As a result everytime someone pushes to main in this repo I will get a notification that this PR has been updated:</p> <p><a href="https://github.com/cucumber/.github/pull/28">cucumber/.github#28</a></p> <p>Since I and many others get a few hundred of these on a weekly basis it is important to have as little noise in here as possible.</p> <p><strong>✨ What's your proposed solution?</strong></p> <p>Publish releases <a href="https://semver.org/">using Semver 2.0.0</a>. Then I'll be able to pin against a specific version of the plugin.</p> <p>Within the Cucumber organisation we use <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/polyglot-release">polyglot-release</a> for this. It is used to release our other GitHub Actions, so this repo will likely work too.</p> <p><strong>⛏️ Have you considered any alternatives or workarounds?</strong></p> <p>I could ignore notifications from the <code>cucumber/.github</code> repo but it is an important repo to keep track of.</p>

mpkorstanje
2023-04-07 01:39:17

*Thread Reply:* This one too, but it is mostly refactoring tests. Not the most pressing work but there can be a few good bite size exercises in there.

https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-jvm/issues/2707

#2707 Reduce build duration by lowering Mockito usage
<p><strong>🤔 What's the problem you've observed?</strong></p> <p>Mockito has a impact on the unit test execution time (seen using IntelliJ Profiler flame graph):</p> <p>Total build duration: 3min17 = 197 seconds<br /> Total test duration : 23.5 seconds<br /> Total Mockito contribution : 4.2 seconds (18% of tests, 2% of build duration)</p> <p>By reducing the usage of Mockito, the test duration can be lowered with two advantages:</p> <p>• this gives the developer a shorter feedback loop. • the energy consumption is lower (green IT), which is important because the cucumber-jvm project is built often (due to PR and renovate bot). 2% is not a lot, but on the long term, it makes a difference.</p> <p><strong>✨ Do you have a proposal for making it better?</strong></p> <p>I didn't check in details, but for example in <code>JavaBackendTest</code>, the <code>@Mock</code> <code>ObjectFactory</code> and <code>Glue</code> could be replaced by fake implementations, which could reduce the class test duration by about 80%.</p>

🙏 help wanted, good first issue, 🏦 debt

*Thread Reply:* If you're going to pick 2716 then the first thing to do would be to checkout the reproducer. See if you can run it and reproduce the problem Then the next step would be checking out Cucumber JVM and see if you can build that. If you run into problems, do a little bit of research and if you can't figure it out ask questions.

Then the next step would be posting a message in the issue to let people know you're working on it. Then you can add the null check and a test and submit a PR with that information.

mpkorstanje
2023-04-07 04:01:03

*Thread Reply:* You can find some more helpful info in https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-jvm/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md but it's not much. Most of the project is Maven Standards so the documentation there should help you, if you haven't already picked it up in your Bachelor.

<https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-jvm/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md | CONTRIBUTING.md>
<p><strong>About to contribute?</strong></p> <p>We appreciate that. Do keep the following in mind:</p> <p>• Before making significant contribution consider discussing the outline of<br /> your solution first. This may avoid a duplication of efforts. • When you send a <a href="https://help.github.com/articles/using-pull-requests">pull requests</a>,<br /> please include tests to go along with it. • Want to paste some code or output? Put ``` on a line above and below your<br /> code/output. See <a href="https://help.github.com/articles/github-flavored-markdown">GitHub Flavored Markdown</a>'s<br /> <em>Fenced Code Blocks</em> for details.</p> <p><strong>Building</strong></p> <p>When building the project for the first time, run:</p> <pre><code>mvn install -DskipTests=true -DskipITs=true -Darchetype.test.skip=true </code></pre> <p>The <code>cucumber-archetype</code> modules integration tests against <code>-SNAPSHOT</code><br /> versions of Cucumber. These must be installed first.</p> <p>Afterwards <code>mvn test</code> or <code>mvn verify</code> should work as expected.</p> <p><strong>Formatting Java</strong></p> <p>The source code is formatted automatically by spotless when running:</p> <pre><code>mvn install </code></pre> <p>To configure IntelliJ IDEA/Eclipse use the configuration files in <code>.spotless/</code>.</p> <p><strong>Formatting XML, Gherkin, ect</strong></p> <p>• UTF-8 file encoding + • LF (UNIX) line endings + • 4 Space indent (no tabs) + • XML • Java • 2 Space indent (no tabs) + • Gherkin</p> <p><code>+</code> These are set automatically if you use an editor/IDE that supports<br /> <a href="http://editorconfig.org/#download">EditorConfig</a>.</p> <p><strong>Building Cucumber-JVM</strong></p> <p>Cucumber-JVM is built with <a href="http://maven.apache.org/">Maven</a>.</p> <pre><code>mvn clean install </code></pre> <p><strong>IDE Setup</strong> <strong>IntelliJ IDEA</strong></p> <pre><code>File -&gt; Open Project -&gt; path/to/cucumber-jvm/pom.xml </code></pre> <p>Your <code>.feature</code> files must be in a folder that IDEA recognises as <em>source</em> or<br /> <em>test</em>. You must also tell IDEA to copy your <code>.feature</code> files to your output<br /> directory:</p> <pre><code>Preferences -&gt; Compiler -&gt; Resource Patterns -&gt; Add `;?**.feature` </code></pre> <p>If you are writing step definitions in a scripting language you must also add<br /> the appropriate file extension for that language as well.</p> <p><strong>Eclipse</strong></p> <p>Just load the root <code>pom.xml</code></p>

<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/issues/60#issuecomment-1622250426">Comment</a> on issue by <a href="https://github.com/blaisep">blaisep</a>

<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors">cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors</a>
GitHub
2023-07-05 11:45:01

*Thread Reply:*

<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/issues/60#issuecomment-1622288410">Comment</a> on issue by <a href="https://github.com/mpkorstanje">mpkorstanje</a>
<https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/issues/60|#60 Java Implementation>
<p>I'm happy to see people contribute, but as this is a GitHub action, I don't believe more than one implementation is needed.</p> <p>As an exercise it would be fine. But actually adding a second implementation to this repo would have a negative value as we would now have two implementations for the same thing of which only one is needed.</p> <p>We can only retire a contributor once.</p>
<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors">cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors</a>
GitHub
2023-07-11 10:11:53

*Thread Reply:*

<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/issues/60#issuecomment-1631191063">Comment</a> on issue by <a href="https://github.com/mattwynne">mattwynne</a>
<https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/issues/60|#60 Java Implementation>
<p>I agree with <a href="https://github.com/mpkorstanje">@mpkorstanje</a>.</p> <p>The reason that some libraries in the Cucumber organization are "polyglot" (e.g. <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/gherkin">https://github.com/cucumber/gherkin</a>) is that we are building and shipping platform-native implementation of that component. For example, this means we have a native Gherkin parser for Go.</p> <p>We don't have the same requirement in this project. GitHub Actions only needs an implementation in one language. As Rien has pointed out, while it might be a useful learning exercise to port the code to Java, it would actually create unnecessary code that will add a maintenance burden.</p> <p>While it's <a href="https://docs.github.com/en/actions/creating-actions/about-custom-actions#docker-container-actions">technically possible to implement a GitHub Action in any programming language</a>, JavaScript (which this TypeScript project compiles to) <a href="https://docs.github.com/en/actions/creating-actions/about-custom-actions#javascript-actions">is the natural choice</a> as GitHub provide libraries for that platform for interacting with the GitHub Actions environment.</p>
<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors">cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors</a>

We're looking into why we only get one page (30 people) when we list members of the org. https://octokit.github.io/rest.js/v20

GitHub
2023-10-19 00:40:45

*Thread Reply:*

<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/issues/76#issuecomment-1770241162">Comment</a> on issue by <a href="https://github.com/cvennevik">cvennevik</a>
<https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/issues/76|#76 List of repos to check for commits is paginated to 30>
<p>(Forgive the drive-by comment, I may be missing important context here!)</p> <p>I think every GitHub API endpoint that returns a list of results paginates, usually 30 results at a time: <a href="https://docs.github.com/en/rest/overview/resources-in-the-rest-api?apiVersion=2022-11-28#pagination">https://docs.github.com/en/rest/overview/resources-in-the-rest-api?apiVersion=2022-11-28#pagination</a></p> <p>The relevant call here should likely also be wrapped in <code>octokit.paginate()</code>, like in the linked commit from a previous issue. It may also be worth scanning the code for other API calls that are unknowingly paginated.</p>
<a href="https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors">cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors</a>

<p>A quick chat with chatGPT gives us a clue for what might work using the GraphQL API:</p> <pre><code>query { organization(login: "&amp;lt;YOUR_ORGANIZATION&amp;gt;") { repositories(first: 100) { edges { node { name owner { login } defaultBranchRef { target { ... on Commit { history(since: "&amp;lt;YOUR_DATE&amp;gt;", author: { email: "&amp;lt;YOUR_USERNAME&amp;gt;@users.noreply.github.com" }) { totalCount edges { node { oid message author { name email date } } } } } } } } } } } } </code></pre>

Blaise Pabon
2023-10-18 12:13:55

So, the summary of today's atypical, fast and furious session was that we found the action producing too many queries and hitting rate limits. The result was issue: https://github.com/cucumber/action-retire-inactive-contributors/issues/77 which pretty much points us in the direction of the next step: consider using the GraphQL API.

#77 Rate limiting on the repolist
<p><strong>👓 What did you see?</strong></p> <p><a href="https://github.com/mattwynne">@mattwynne</a> noticed that we hit rate limiting when the action runs:<br /> see:<br /> <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/.github/actions/runs/6565058933/job/17832737164#step:3:204">https://github.com/cucumber/.github/actions/runs/6565058933/job/17832737164#step:3:204</a></p> <p><strong>✅ What did you expect to see?</strong></p> <p>The list should complete, instead it gets interrupted.</p> <p><strong>📦 Which tool/library version are you using?</strong> <strong>🔬 How could we reproduce it?</strong></p> <p>Steps to reproduce the behavior:</p> <ol><li>Install '...' version '...' Action <code>0.4.0</code></li><li>Create a file called '....'</li><li>Run command '....'</li><li>See error '....'</li> </ol> <p><strong>📚 Any additional context?</strong></p> <hr /> <p><em>This text was originally generated from a <a href="https://docs.github.com/en/communities/using-templates-to-encourage-useful-issues-and-pull-requests/about-issue-and-pull-request-templates">template</a>, then edited by hand. <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/.github/edit/main/.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/bug_report.md">You can modify the template here.</a></em></p>

*Thread Reply:* Frankly, I was just about to give up when @mpkorstanje sent me a encouraging word.

So, for me to get excited about the work, I would like to add some variety to the code. The github action we built is super cool and one of the rare examples of lessons in TDD that have a practical result.

However, it's written in TypeScript • TypeScript is already well represented in Cucumber. • Typescript's peculiarities result in us spending more time wrestling with dependencies and syntax than doing actual work. I would prefer to have projects in a proper programming language, like Python, Ruby or Rust.

Blaise Pabon
2023-11-01 08:55:51

*Thread Reply:* I would also like to include activities which exercise the full cucumber/gherkin stack and help us access a broader range of features, and to engage contributors with a broader range of skills

This is motivated by a desire to get some of the gurus with deep gherkin experience (looking at you @Jon Acker, @Erik Huelsmann)

#264 Using C++ standard library where possible instead of boost
<p><strong>Summary</strong></p> <p>Using C++ standard library where possible instead of boost.</p> <p><strong>Details</strong></p> <p>Many boost functionality moved into the C++ standard library over the years. This PR uses the functionality form the standard library instead of boost.</p> <p>The minimal required C++ standard is C++17.</p> <p><strong>Motivation and Context</strong></p> <p>This is a modernization of the code base.</p> <p><strong>How Has This Been Tested?</strong></p> <p>No functional changes were made. All tests run in the CI.</p> <p><strong>Types of changes</strong></p> <p>☑︎ Bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue). ☐ New feature (non-breaking change which adds functionality). ☐ Breaking change (fix or feature that would cause existing functionality to not work as expected).</p> <p><strong>Checklist:</strong></p> <p>☑︎ It is my own work, its copyright is implicitly assigned to the project and no substantial part of it has been copied from other sources (including <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/">Stack Overflow</a>). In rare occasions this is acceptable, like in CMake modules where the original copyright information should be kept. ☑︎ I'm using the same code standards as the existing code (indentation, spacing, variable naming, ...). ☑︎ I've added tests for my code. ☑︎ I have verified whether my change requires changes to the documentation ☑︎ My change either requires no documentation change or I've updated the documentation accordingly. ☑︎ My branch has been rebased to main, keeping only relevant commits.</p>

Going by https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-cpp/issues/242 the project currently doesn’t have a maintainer. You can pick up that title if you want.

#242 WANTED: A new maintainer :wrench::woman-raising-hand::man-raising-hand::skin-tone-5::raising_hand::skin-tone-3:
<p>This project has had pull requests piling up for a few years now.</p> <p>There are some <a href="https://techgaun.github.io/active-forks/index.html#cucumber/cucumber-cpp">active forks</a> so clearly people are using still it, but we sadly don't have anyone here within the Cucumber org taking responsibility for keeping this copy up to date.</p> <p>I haven't seen <a href="https://github.com/paoloambrosio">@paoloambrosio</a> or <a href="https://github.com/muggenhor">@muggenhor</a> around these parts in a while, so I suspect we may be looking for a new maintainer (or two!). None of the rest of the core team use C++ regularly, so we really need someone who uses the tool to help us look after it.</p> <p><a href="https://github.com/jermus67">@jermus67</a>, <a href="https://github.com/rogerdubbs">@rogerdubbs</a>, <a href="https://github.com/silvergasp">@silvergasp</a>, <a href="https://github.com/dmeehan1968">@dmeehan1968</a>, <a href="https://github.com/saimusdev">@saimusdev</a> you've all made commits on your own fork fairly recently. Would any of you be interested in helping keep this library up to date? Or do you have any friends who might? 😁</p> <p>In return, you will get the 🎉 and ❤️ of the Cucumber community, and a great new way to spend your spare time 😄</p>

#77 Rate limiting on the repolist
<p><strong>👓 What did you see?</strong></p> <p><a href="https://github.com/mattwynne">@mattwynne</a> noticed that we hit rate limiting when the action runs:<br /> see:<br /> <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/.github/actions/runs/6565058933/job/17832737164#step:3:204">https://github.com/cucumber/.github/actions/runs/6565058933/job/17832737164#step:3:204</a></p> <p><strong>✅ What did you expect to see?</strong></p> <p>The list should complete, instead it gets interrupted.</p> <p><strong>📦 Which tool/library version are you using?</strong> <strong>🔬 How could we reproduce it?</strong></p> <p>Steps to reproduce the behavior:</p> <ol><li>Install '...' version '...' Action <code>0.4.0</code></li><li>Run the action against the cucumber org in read-only mode.</li><li>See error</li> </ol> <pre><code> HttpError: API rate limit exceeded for user ID 19260. If you reach out to GitHub Support for help, please include the request ID 0848:5194:15A201C:1657A1D:653026E0. </code></pre> <p><strong>📚 Any additional context?</strong></p> <hr /> <p><em>This text was originally generated from a <a href="https://docs.github.com/en/communities/using-templates-to-encourage-useful-issues-and-pull-requests/about-issue-and-pull-request-templates">template</a>, then edited by hand. <a href="https://github.com/cucumber/.github/edit/main/.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/bug_report.md">You can modify the template here.</a></em></p>
